This repo holds my Claude Code presets — agents, slash commands, and the
global CLAUDE.md memory file — so I can sync them into any environment
in a single step.

## Install in any project (one-liner)

Paste this into a Claude Code session, or run it in any shell:

    curl -fsSL https://raw.githubusercontent.com/agastyataqi/trial4claudeforworkidkwhatimdoingatallsoimavibecodernow/main/bootstrap.sh | bash

It pulls the latest `main` and copies into `~/.claude/`:

  - `.claude/agents/`   -> `~/.claude/agents/`
  - `.claude/commands/` -> `~/.claude/commands/`
  - `CLAUDE.md`         -> `~/.claude/CLAUDE.md`

Idempotent. Safe to re-run any time to refresh.

## IMPORTANT: restart Claude Code after running it

Claude Code scans `~/.claude/commands/` and `~/.claude/agents/` **once,
at session startup**, to build the slash-command registry. Files that
arrive after that scan — including files copied by the one-liner — will
**not** appear as `/commands` in the current session.

Workflow:

  1. Open Claude Code in the new project.
  2. Run the one-liner above as your first prompt.
  3. **Close Claude Code and reopen it.**
  4. Slash commands (`/council`, `/done`, etc.) and the CLAUDE.md memory
     are now active. They stay active for every future session in that
     environment — you only do this once per environment.

If you ever need a command in the *same* session you just installed
into, ask Claude in plain English ("run the council workflow on X") —
Claude can read the command file directly without going through the
slash registry.

## Inside this repo

Working in this repo directly? The `SessionStart` hook in
`.claude/settings.json` already syncs the same files automatically when
a session starts, so the one-liner is unnecessary here. The same
restart caveat applies if `~/.claude/` was empty before this session.
